sting -- authenticated PNG steganography built on gisp
======================================================

sting hides a secret inside an ordinary-looking PNG image.  The secret is
never embedded in the clear: it is first encrypted by gisp
(XChaCha20-Poly1305 with an Argon2id-derived key), and only the resulting
opaque container is scattered across the carrier's pixels.

Design goals
------------

  * Confidentiality and integrity come entirely from gisp.  sting treats the
    ciphertext as an opaque blob and never sees, derives, or stores the
    passphrase, so gisp's hardened key handling is not weakened.

  * Statistical undetectability.  At most 3% of a carrier's usable colour
    samples are ever touched, and the tool uses LSB *matching* (+/-1
    embedding) rather than LSB *replacement*, so it produces none of the
    pair-of-values histogram signature that replacement is known for.  The
    touched samples are spread across the whole image by a keyed,
    version-independent pseudo-random permutation (SHAKE-256).

Requirements
------------

  * Python 3
  * Pillow            (PNG decode/encode)   -- MIT-CMU licence
  * NumPy             (vectorised LSB math) -- BSD-3-Clause licence
  * gisp              (the encryption back end)

On a Debian/Ubuntu system:  apt install python3-pil python3-numpy
On Arch:                     pacman -S python-pillow python-numpy

Building and installing
-----------------------

sting is pure Python; "building" only generates the launcher script.

    make                 # create build/sting
    make check           # run the self-test (uses gisp if it is found)
    sudo make install    # install under /usr/local by default

    make install prefix=$HOME/.local     # a home-directory install
    make uninstall                       # remove it again

To run straight from a checkout without installing, just use ./sting, or
  python3 -m stinglib.

Usage
-----

    sting --hide    -c cover.png -i secret.txt -o innocent.png
    sting --extract -i innocent.png -o secret.txt
    sting --capacity -c cover.png

A path of '-' selects standard input or standard output, and the passphrase
options are forwarded to gisp, so sting drops into the same pipelines:

    tar c dir | sting -H -c cover.png -i - -o - --passphrase-fd 3 3<key > s.png
    sting -X -i - -o - --passphrase-fd 3 3<key < s.png | tar x

See the manual page sting(1) for the full option list.

Layout
------

    sting            run-in-place launcher
    sting.in         template for the installed launcher (Makefile fills it)
    stinglib/        the Python package
      constants.py     identity, exit codes, container format
      errors.py        exception types that steer exit status
      keystream.py     SHAKE-256 permutations and bit helpers
      carrier.py       PNG decode/encode and the usable-sample model
      stego.py         the embed / extract core
      backend.py       the gisp subprocess boundary
      streams.py       stdin/stdout- and file-aware byte I/O
      cli.py           argument parsing and the mode handlers
    tests/run-tests.py self-test
    sting.1          manual page
    Makefile         build/install
    COPYING          the GNU General Public License, version 3

